The formula to calculate the current ratio is as follows. 
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Current ratio}&=\dfrac{\text{Current asset}}{\text{Current Liabilities}} 
\end{aligned}$$

The formula to calculate the quick ratio is as follows. 
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Quick ratio}&=\dfrac{\text{Current asset - Inventories}}{\text{Current Liabilities}} 
\end{aligned}$$

The formula to calculate the cash ratio is as follows. 
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Cash ratio}&=\dfrac{\text{Cash}}{\text{Current Liabilities}} 
\end{aligned}$$

## Requirement e- (1.) Debt to equity ratio and (2.) Equity multiplier
\
The **debt to equity ratio** indicates the portion of debt for every $1 of equity. This can be calculated using the following formula. 

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Debt to Equity ratio}&=\dfrac{\text{Total debt}}{\text{Total equity}}
\end{aligned}$$

The **equity multiplier** tells us how much of the company's total assets is financed by the shareholders. This is calculated using the following formula. 

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Equity multiplier}&=\dfrac{\text{Total asset}}{\text{Total equity}}
\end{aligned}$$
